# Never Push Without Verification

`git push` (and any variant: `--force`, `--force-with-lease`, push tags, push to a
new branch, push via `gh pr create` with auto-push, etc.) requires explicit user
confirmation in the current message **before** the command is run. Past approvals
from earlier in the session do not count.

## Required Flow

1. Show the user exactly what would be pushed: branch name, remote, commit list
   (one-line `git log --oneline @{upstream}..HEAD` or `origin/main..HEAD`).
2. Ask for confirmation in plain text. Wait for an unambiguous yes in the next
   user message.
3. Only then run the push.

## Examples

BAD:
```
git commit -m "fix"
git push origin main
```

BAD (rolled into another command):
```
git push origin HEAD && gh pr create ...
```

GOOD:
```
# After committing, surface a summary:
# "Ready to push 2 commits to origin/feature-x:
#    abc1234 fix: handle null case
#    def5678 test: add coverage
#  Confirm push? (yes/no)"
# Wait for user to reply "yes" in the next message, then push.
```

## Scope

Applies to every git remote operation that mutates a remote: `git push`,
`git push --force*`, `git push --tags`, `gh pr create` when it implicitly pushes,
and any wrapper script that invokes one of these. Does not apply to read-only
remote ops (`git fetch`, `git pull --rebase` into a clean tree, `gh pr view`).
